The paper deals with image classification, specifically in the domain of hyperspectral images. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also introduces a novel approach for learning on distributions, which involves representing them in reproducing kernel Hilbert spaces (RKHS). This suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper uses support vector machines (SVM) as the classification technique, which is a popular machine learning algorithm. This further supports the argument that the paper belongs to the machine learning sub-category. The paper also leverages on both spatial and spectral information in the data, which suggests that it may belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with image data, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
